}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 After ridding themselves from a nuclear power plant just after its completion, some concerned Austrians used to joke, \ldblquote where does all the electricity come from?  Well, of course it comes from the socket! \rdblquote  So, by analogy, one could ask, \ldblquote Where does all our money come from? \rdblquote  and rightly respond, \ldblquote from the teller machine,\rdblquote  or more generally, \ldblquote from the bank! \rdblquote  Wheres in the electrical case the answer appears polemic and foolish, in the money case it is exactly correct: money is \ldblquote produced\rdblquote  by the bank; \ldblquote out of thin air,\rdblquote  or, stated differently, \ldblquote out of nothing.\rdblquote \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Why, then, do we have so little money if it can be created so easily?  Because the essence of money is its scarcity, or at least the impression of scarcity.{\xe{\v scarcity}} For if money was abundand and readily available everywhere, or if anybody could have access to it effortlessly \ldblquote on demand,\rdblquote  it would get inflated and be worth nothing. This, in a sentence, refutes monetary systems without interest or privilege.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 So money appears to be both producible \ldblquote our of thin air,\rdblquote  and at the same time valuable. How to achieve that apparent contradiction is straightforward: first, some \ldblquote authorities\rdblquote  have to be entrusted with the creation of money; and second, some provisions for a appropriation of money should render, at least the impression of, scarcity.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 How did I start to think about money?  About fifteen years ago, my colleage Gerhard Adam was passing me the seemingly simple question of the origin of money as we were having lunch at the cafeteria. He plainly asked me, \ldblquote how exactly is money created? \rdblquote  I still remember that, after some attempts of \ldblquote explaining\rdblquote  this to Gerhard and myself, I ended up staring at my half-eaten salad in bewilderment.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 I almost gasped. I could not tell. I was at a miserable loss when it came to money creation. I felt humiliated and perplexed.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Now, fifteen years later, and after many books, discussions and thoughts on the subject, I am convinced that I can answer that question, at least \ldblquote for all practical purposes\rdblquote  (abbreviated by {\i fapp} by physicists). Yet I had to absorb some uncomforting facts.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Indeed, at some point I felt like the main character in Carpenter\rquote s 1988 movie {\i They Live,} who, after about 30 minutes into that movie, puts on some supposedly normal pair of sunglasses, only to discover that \ldblquote reality\rdblquote  and the \ldblquote surrounding environment,\rdblquote  at least as seen through these glasses, appears to be totally different from what he was conditioned to believe: Imprinted everywhere are manipulative messages, and an alien race is intermingling with the locals.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 I am about to suggest that we have been deceived into believing that money is a relatively benign, passive and unsuspicious entity and medium of exchange\~{Samuelson and Nordhaus} (2004); {Begg {\i et\~al.}} (2005); {Kyrer and Penker} (2000), whereas effectively monetary schemes \emdash  whether they are based on fiat money with no intrinsic value, or on commodities such as silver or gold \emdash  present a systematic method to extract and reappropriate the wealth of nations towards institutions and goals which most of the time would not have found public support by the \ldblquote common man,\rdblquote  the \ldblquote middle class,\rdblquote  and by \ldblquote capitalists\rdblquote  alike.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The gist of my argument, in a nutshell, is a pretty unspectacular claim: that {\i all sorts of money} tend to get corrupted; an effect that in the long run renders money worthless and eventually deprive people holding it. By issuing new money and assuring new generations that this time will be different, the cycle of emergence and corruption starts over again. Under very general assumptions this abusive corruption and misuse of power is inevitable, stringent, and thus should come as no surprise.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The main reason for this pattern of corruption is \ldblquote money multiplication\rdblquote  in various forms. Examples are the degradation of coins by including less precious metals, issuing more and more notes covering less and less commodities (e.g. silver and gold) per note; or in the present \ldblquote fiat\rdblquote  money system \ldblquote covered\rdblquote  merely by our belief in it, by creating money out of \ldblquote thin air.\rdblquote \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The beneficiaries of this Ponzi-type pyramid scheme are {\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 \bullet\tab the state, which receives money without direct taxation (which always is unpopular, painful and difficult to implement); of course the extra money \ldblquote printed\rdblquote  in exchange of government debt (i.e., bonds) contributes to a general decline in value (inflation), and thus to an {\i indirect taxation;} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 \bullet\tab people holding money or assets if (and only if) they are able to realize {\i cumulative advantages} {\xe{\v cumulative advantage}} (sometimes also referred to {\i compound interest} {\xe{\v compound interest}} or the Matthews Effect\~{Merton} (1968)); {\xe{\v Matthews Effect}} \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 \bullet\tab lucky speculants, as well as \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li600\fi-300 \bullet\tab the \ldblquote Money Trust\rdblquote  \emdash  consisting of all money issuing entities, in particular today\rquote s \ldblquote central banks\rdblquote  as well as the banking and financial industry in general, acquiring \ldblquote something for nothing\rdblquote \~{Soddy} (1934) by collecting {\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li1200\fi-300 \bullet\tab valuable assets through monetization, as well as \par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb50 \li1200\fi-300 \bullet\tab interest through the issue of fiat money in exchange of debt certificates (mostly government bonds). \par
}}\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \sb100 \fi0 States and all forms of governments react decisevely, radically and brutally by extracting wealth from their citicens if necessary. From today\rquote s perspective it appears hardly believable that in the last century totalitarian dictatorships such as Soviet Bolshevism, but also democracies such as Roosevelt\rquote s United States of America (from 1933 to 1975) alike prohibited the possesion of gold by their citizens and penalized infringements with heavy sanctions. In history, sovereigns and states have \ldblquote stolen\rdblquote  the wealth of their subordinates and citizens a zillion of times, and they will do so again and again if they consider it necessary. Thus effectively monetary policy and instruments are just other, \ldblquote implicit and softer\rdblquote  ways to extract valuable assets from their citizens.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 To be able to recognize fully the impact of any monetary system, we must acknowledge historical, psychological, philosophical, and in particular also political issues alike. Thereby, I do not wish to impose any kind of ideological agenda, besides, probably, the opportunistic guiding principle subsumed by the latin phrase {\i \ldblquote cui bono? \rdblquote } meaning \ldblquote to whose benefit? \rdblquote  Furthermore, I suggest to uphold an advice by Sigmund Freud {\xe{\v Freud, Sigmund}} to his successors\~{Freud} (1999), to be aware of the dangers caused by {\scaps0\b0\i \ldblquote {{\u8230\'85}}\~temptations to project, what [[the analyst]] in dull self-perception recognizes as the peculiarities of his own personality, as generally valid theory into science\~{{\u8230\'85}}\~.\rdblquote } Economies are thereby treated as a \ldblquote client-patients,\rdblquote  and whatever findings come up are accepted \ldblquote as is,\rdblquote  without any immediate emphasis or judgment.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Now you might want to wave this off as sounding suspiciosly like a weirdo telling you revisionist conspiracy theories. Actually, I ensure you that I myself tried hard to convice myself that \ldblquote all is well\rdblquote  with our monetary system, besides some wackos claiming to uphold the \ldblquote true truth\rdblquote  while disseminating crappy thoughts about this or that. If you think that is the case, I suggest you rather stop reading and enjoy yourself as long as you can immediately.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 If you want to belive in some {\scaps0\b0\i \ldblquote Sparefroh\rdblquote } {\xe{\v Sparefroh}} mentality I have no intention to trouble you. Let me, as a last word of warning, tell you though, that, as has been pointed out by the Austrian poet {\i Heimito von Doderer}, {\scaps0\b0\i it requires some intelligence to acknowledge one\rquote s own dumbness.} Thus, one should keep in mind that for those not willing to, or being incapable of, providing this intelligence and willingness to cope with certain situations, a lot of mostly unpleasant and unexpected surprises might happen throughout their lifes. But then, they might just as well be lucky. Evading troubling opinions as well as enjoying oneself without too many intellectual concerns regarding things which one might not be able to change anyway, is not totally unreasonable.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 For those Readers still lingering on with this text, I would like to point out that in what follows I have tried to explain my thoughts as short, clear and comprehensible as possible. Being a theoretical physicist myself, I find particularly frustrating any vain tendency to heavily formalize and mathematize macroeconomic processes and issues; endevours which lead to nowhere most of the time. That is, there is not much preditive power in many macroeconomic formisms. Of course, I am not against formalization as such \emdash  just on the contrary!  \emdash  but the reductionist program fails for \ldblquote complicated,\rdblquote  \ldblquote complex\rdblquote  systems which cannot be standardized and reduced to simple behaviors, which can be composed into, or scaled to, macroeconomic scales.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Thus, very little mathematics is presented; instead I suggest to use analytical, critical reasoning and empirical evidence as far as possible. After all, life is too short to spoil it with an unnecessary amount of useles formalism.\par
\pard\qj\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The title was chosen because, despite all negative consequences, the author can think of no \ldblquote reasonable\rdblquote  alternative to fiat money, thus in a very general sense he is afraid that, despite its apparent inherent and irreducible lack of stability and the resulting inevitable crises, there is no feasible alternative to it.\par
